  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">HIAS PSYCHOSOCIAL ASSISTANCE, LIVELIHOODS AND DURABLE SOLUTIONS PROGRAM FOR COLOMBIAN REFUGEES IN PANAMA</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">HIAS&#x2019; program seeks to improve durable solution responses for Colombian refugees through direct therapeutic activities, psychosocial support, job skills development, capacity building, and support for integration into local communities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Objective 1: To improve the mental health of Colombian refugees by providing psychosocial support designed to alleviate the trauma and related effects of violence and abuse suffered as well as the difficulties faced during their search for durable solutions.

Objective 2: To improve access to durable solutions through the provision of orientation, information, and specific direct assistance.

Objective 3: To build and strengthen the capacity of national and local private and public organizations to address the population needs and improve the fulfillment of their rights and access to services.

Objective 4: To promote access to dignified livelihoods (formal employment or income generation activities) through vocational training and development of job skills.

Objective 5: To assist in the integration of refugee populations into local host communities through community engagement outreach and informal educational activities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Particularly vulnerable refugees and families receive individual psychosocial support from psychologists. HIAS psychologists identify and monitor those with specific needs, such as survivors of GBV or torture; unaccompanied and separated minors; single mothers; women at risk; the sick, elderly, or disabled; victims of discrimination due to their gender identity; those with legal and/or physical protection needs; and other minorities.</narrative>
  </description>
